         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>l.2 Perhaps a feminine name of Libyan origin. </p>
            <p>l.3 Presumably cognomen of the donor's father or husband. </p>
            <p> line 4 Either ὅλον or perhaps from a word indicating the construction decorated, eg. Θόλον, περίβολον.</p>
            <p> For σκουτλῶσις and similar forms involving translitteration into Greek from words on the Latin Root of Scutula, 
               see examples collected by Robert, REG 1957, p. 362, n.1 <!-- check --> and Hellenica IX. 48, XI. 52; 
               Robert concluded that it means a veneer or stucco application to a wall (not to a floor as the dictionaries claim) which may be painted. 
               As he observes, in this case the plaque bearing the inscription is part of the work.</p>
            <p> The donor's heirs presumably executed his or her testamentary instructions and added the marble floor paving indicated by ἔδαφος.</p>
         </div>
         
